Task Domain and Input Structure:
- Each input is a single example containing a 'text' field. 
- The 'text' may describe a geometric figure directly (name or definition) or refer to one indirectly, e.g., through an SVG path data string that outlines its points.
- There may be a list of options, but you must ONLY select from the allowed labels: B, C, D, E, F, G, I, J, or K.

Category Definitions and Distinctions:
- B = Heptagon (polygon with exactly 7 straight sides/corners)
- C = Hexagon (polygon with exactly 6 straight sides/corners)
- D = Kite (quadrilateral with 2 pairs of adjacent sides equal; must fit the standard mathematical definition as a kite)
- E = Line (single, straight, one-dimensional segment between two points; only assign if the input describes exactly this, NOT a polygon or multi-segment path)
- F = Octagon (polygon with exactly 8 straight sides/corners)
- G = Pentagon (polygon with exactly 5 straight sides/corners)
- I = Sector (portion of a circle bounded by two radii and an arc; only assign if described explicitly)
- J = Triangle (polygon with exactly 3 straight sides/corners)
- K = Ellipse (mathematically defined oval shape; includes any figure described as an ellipse)

SVG Path Analysis:
- For SVG path elements, determine the number of straight segments by analyzing the sequence of “L” command points and whether the path returns to its starting point.
- Count unique corners (coordinate pairs). A closed, single loop path connecting N points is a polygon with N sides.
- When classifying polygons, base it strictly on the number of sides as indicated by the SVG or explicit description, not on names in the text unless those names match the mathematical definition.
- Only assign 'D' if the figure is a quadrilateral meeting the detailed kite criteria, not merely any four-sided figure.

Ambiguity and Prioritization:
- In case of ambiguity or if the figure could fit multiple categories, use all information in the text or path to make the most mathematically precise assignment.
- If the shape or path doesn't match any category perfectly, pick the closest reasonable match based on the description and typical geometric standards.
- Never guess a category by superficial word order, prominence in options, or commonality; always reason from shape definition or SVG geometric structure.

Label Output Rules:
- Output ONLY one of the allowed labels (B, C, D, E, F, G, I, J, K), with NO explanations or extra commentary.
- NO punctuation, extra formatting, or text outside the single category label.
- Only one label per input, even if the input seems ambiguous or could belong to more than one category.

Error Prevention Reminders:
- Do NOT assign D, E, I, or K unless the description fits their definitions precisely.
- Do NOT infer triangles, pentagons, hexagons, etc., by association or name in options—always count the actual path segments or sides.
- Always use the standard geometric definitions as provided above, taking care with edge cases: count sides on polygons, check for kite-specific properties for D, sector properties for I, ellipse for K, and ensure a single unbroken straight line for E.

Process for Each Input:
1. Read the 'text' field fully and carefully.
2. If given an SVG path, count the sides or analyze the structure to determine the geometric type.
3. Match the description or path to the precise category definition.
4. Output the correct label—B, C, D, E, F, G, I, J, or K—alone.

By closely following these instructions, you minimize errors from option confusion, superficial cues, or improper geometric categorization.
